7) In Apache Spark, data skew refers to an uneven distribution of data across partitions, where a few keys hold a large portion of the data, causing some tasks to run much longer than others.”

🧠 Simple Scenario

👉 You run a join on user_id

user_id = 1 → 10,00,000 records  
user_id = 2 → 100 records  
user_id = 3 → 50 records
One partition gets huge data
Others get very little
============================

8) In Apache Spark, data skew can be mitigated by redistributing data more evenly across partitions or avoiding heavy keys during shuffle operations.”

🧠 Simple Scenario

👉 Problem:

user_id = 1 → 10,00,000 rows  
others → very small

👉 One partition overloaded → job slow ❌

🚀 Solutions
🔹 1. Salting (Most Effective)

👉 Split heavy keys into smaller chunks

from pyspark.sql.functions import rand, floor

df1 = df1.withColumn("salt", floor(rand()*10))
df2 = df2.withColumn("salt", floor(rand()*10))

df1.join(df2, ["user_id", "salt"]).show()

👉 Heavy key distributed across partitions ✔

🔹 2. Broadcast Join

👉 If one table is small

from pyspark.sql.functions import broadcast

df_large.join(broadcast(df_small), "user_id").show()

👉 Avoids shuffle ✔

🔹 3. Repartition by Key
df = df.repartition("user_id")

👉 Improves distribution (but not always enough)

🔹 4. Use AQE (Adaptive Query Execution)
spark.conf.set("spark.sql.adaptive.enabled", "true")

👉 Spark automatically handles skew ✔

🔹 5. Filter Early
df = df.filter("user_id IS NOT NULL")

👉 Reduce unnecessary data ✔

⚙️ Key Insight

👉
Goal = balance workload across partitions

🎤 Interview Answer

👉
“To fix data skew in Spark, techniques like salting, broadcasting small tables, repartitioning data, and enabling Adaptive Query Execution can be used to distribute data more evenly and avoid performance bottlenecks.”


